---
import { withBase } from '../../lib/url';
import Prose from '../../layouts/Prose.astro';
import QuoteList from '../../components/QuoteList.astro';
import { TECHNIQUES } from '../../lib/techniques';

const t = TECHNIQUES.find((x) => x.slug === 'aspects-and-company')!;
---

<Prose
  title={t.title}
  description={t.description}
  crumbs={[{ name: 'Techniques', href: '/techniques/' }, { name: t.title }]}
  kicker="Technique"
  jsonLd={[{ '@type': 'Article', headline: t.title }]}
>
  <p>
    The houses of a chart behold one another as the signs do, by aspect: each house has its
    sextiles, squares, and trines on either side, and its opposition across the chart. Beside the
    aspects, neighbouring houses keep company in fixed pairs. Both relations show how the figures in
    other houses help or hinder the matter in question.
  </p>

  <h2>Count the aspects</h2>
  <ol>
    <li>Fix the house you are reading, usually the first or the seventh.</li>
    <li>Count to the houses that aspect it, on either side, by inclusive counting, where the house itself is the first counted.</li>
    <li>Note the aspect and its direction. An aspect against the order of the houses is <em>dexter</em> and the stronger; one following the order is <em>sinister</em>. The dexter-stronger rule is a modern refinement.</li>
    <li>Judge by the figure standing in the beholding house, not by the aspect alone. A trine with an ill figure is still ill; a square with a strong, agreeing figure can help.</li>
  </ol>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Aspect</th><th>Houses apart</th><th>Nature</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>Sextile</td><td>2</td><td>Mild friendship, the weakest of the four</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Square</td><td>3</td><td>Hard, but judged by the figure</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Trine</td><td>4</td><td>Strong friendship</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Opposition</td><td>opposite (6)</td><td>Hard, though it can agree if the figures agree</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h2>Read the company</h2>
  <ol>
    <li>Take a significator and look at its companion house, in the fixed pairs: the first with the second, the third with the fourth, and so through the chart.</li>
    <li>Name the kind of company: simple (the same figure), demi-simple (figures sharing a planet), compound (contrary figures), or by the points on high (their top lines agree).</li>
    <li>Read it as support, not perfection. Good company strengthens a significator; ill company undermines it.</li>
  </ol>

  <h2>In the sources</h2>
  <p>
    Cattan sets out the aspects and the friendships and enmities of the figures. Friendly figures
    aspecting the house of the question aid it, and hostile figures hinder it:
  </p>
  <QuoteList topic="aspects" />
  <p>
    On the company of houses, Cattan distinguishes simple, half-simple, and compound company, with
    worked examples from his own practice:
  </p>
  <QuoteList topic="company" />
  <p>
    Crowley's worked example shows how these findings are read together in practice:
    <a href={withBase('/library/crowley/method-of-judging/')}>the General Method of Judging a Figure</a>.
  </p>
</Prose>
